title: Maiorana: Stephon Gilmore coming up big for Bills
text:
NASHVILLE, Tenn. If nothing else, we know one thing about these Rex Ryan Buffalo Bills: They have a healthy dose of resiliency running through their veins. All I have to do is scroll back through my Twitter timeline Sunday and look at the tweets I was getting, and the tweets I was sending, to know that the vast majority of Bills followers thought the Tennessee game was a lost cause. The way the offense was playing, that 10-0 Titans lead might as well have been 100-0 because it just didn't seem plausible that Buffalo would score once, let alone twice.
But the Bills didn't share that same doom and gloom outlook. They stuck with it, kept "chopping wood" as Richie Incognito said, and pulled out a 14-13 victory that could prove huge by the end of the season, given that it was an AFC game.
"It shows the pysche of the guys in this locker room how we keep battling," said defensive end Jerry Hughes. "It was tremendous to get a win on the road, so hopefully we can build on this and keep it rolling."
Upon Further Review, it was just as ugly Monday as it was Sunday, but all that matters is Buffalo is 3-2 rather than 2-3.

1. Stephon Gilmore . This guy is really playing well, and I would have to believe some of the Gilmore hate will start to subside. For some reason fans have really ridden the 2012 first-round draft choice, and while he may not have been an instant star his first two years, he was tremendous last year, and he's been even better this year. He had three more pass breakups against the Titans, plus the game-securing interception with 1:32 left to play.
2. Tyrod Taylor. Midway through the third quarter, I could not have envisioned including the quarterback in the "things I liked" section. He was terrible in the first half for the second week in a row, and getting no help from anyone on offense, it didn't seem possible that he could turn it around. In the end, his passing stats were ugly — 109 yards — but he single-handedly won this game with his running and scrambling. There's no way Buffalo wins that one with Matt Cassel or EJ Manuel on the field.
3. Marcell Dareus. The big man had his best game of the season. He was a force inside and played a huge role in bottling up the Titans running game. Like the Bills, Tennessee has a young and inexperienced quarterback in rookie Marcus Mariota, and it needs to be able to run to help the kid out. But Dareus and company controlled the line and Bishop Sankey and Dexter McCluster totaled a mere 40 yards.

Three things I didn't like
1. The right side of the Bills offensive line. Tackle Seantrel Henderson was abysmal in this game, and guard John Miller wasn't much better. Both struggled mightily against a sturdy Titans line led by by DT Jurrell Casey and rush LB Derrick Morgan. ProFootballFocus has Miller ranked as the second-worst guard (76th out of 77 qualifiers) in their pass blocking efficiency metric this season. That's Erik Pears territory, but he's a rookie, so I'll cut him some slack for now. Henderson is a second-year player with 21 career NFL starts. He has to be play better or he's going to get Tyrod Taylor killed. Ryan said of Henderson, "It was probably his worst game of the season."
2. Robert Woods and Percy Harvin. What was that all about? One combined catch for four yards in a game where the Bills really needed them, given their disastrous situation at running back. It has become painfully clear how important Sammy Watkins is to the offense. He is the most indispensable player, moreso than LeSean McCoy, because when Watkins is on the field, the defense has to account for him and it opens things up for everyone else. Ryan said Monday he thinks Watkins will be back for the Bengals game. That's good news.
3. The officials. Once again, another game where you just shake your head and wonder what these guys are watching. The personal foul penalty on Corey Graham on Tennessee's penultimate possession was, as team president Russ Brandon said after the game, "criminal." It's not often I throw my hands up in the press box, but I did on that one. Seriously, getting off the field on third down in the National Penalty League is next to impossible sometimes because these officials just seem like they're looking even harder to call something. Thankfully for the Bills, that call didn't cost them the game because they stopped the Titans on that drive and forced a punt.

Maiorana: Bills showed some true resiliency in victory
Stat pack
5 - Players in NFL history, and only the second in the Super Bowl era (since 1966), with 100-plus passing yards, 70-plus rushing yards, and a pass reception in the same game. Tyrod Taylor joined the list, and became the first player to accomplish the feat since Randall Cunningham of the Eagles in 1987.
2009 - That was the last time a non-quarterback completed a pass for the Bills before Chris Hogan's completion Sunday. Fred Jackson hit Lee Evans for a 27-yard touchdown, and guess where that happened: In Tennessee at what was then Adelphia Coliseum in what proved to be Dick Jauron's final game as Buffalo head coach.
2 - Catches by Marquise Goodwin, which doubles his production from 2014, when he caught just one pass.
2 - Games out of 73 in his career where Percy Harvin didn't catch a pass. The second came Sunday, the first was in 2014 playing for the Jets, and both games were played at Tennessee's Nissan Stadium.
Bills outside linebacker Nigel Bradham pulls down Titans quarterback Marcus Mariota during the fourth quarter at Nissan Stadium. (Photo: Jae S. Lee / The Tennessean)
Looking ahead
When the schedule came out, many of us looked at this Cincinnati game at the Ralph and chalked it up as a victory for the Bills. Which again proves just how silly that exercise is. Now, this looks like a game that Buffalo will have to play its absolute best in to win as the Bengals come to town 5-0, one of the hottest teams in the NFL.
Cincinnati, with Andy Dalton playing the best he's ever played, rallied from a 24-7 fourth-quarter deficit Sunday to knock off the defending NFC champion Seattle Seahawks as Dalton threw for 331 yards. If the Bills don't get some key players back on offense this week, it might be awfully tough to outscore the Bengals.
